Chapter 1. Admin Guide

1.1. Overview

   The rust_dynamic_blacklist module provides a live-reload
   file-based blacklist for blocking SIP traffic by source IP,
   User-Agent, domain, or any arbitrary string value. The blacklist
   file is loaded at startup into each worker process. Matching can
   be exact (HashSet lookup) or prefix-based (linear scan of
   prefixes).

   This module is useful for blocking known scanner IPs, malicious
   User-Agent strings, or spam domains without restarting OpenSIPS.

1.2. How it works

   At worker initialization, each process loads the blacklist file
   and parses it line-by-line. Blank lines and lines starting with
   # are skipped.

   In "exact" mode, entries are stored in a HashSet for O(1)
   lookup. The value passed to rust_check_blacklist() must match
   an entry exactly (case-sensitive).

   In "prefix" mode, entries are stored as a list of prefixes. The
   value is checked against each prefix using starts_with(). This
   allows blocking entire IP subnets (e.g., "192.168.1.") or
   User-Agent families (e.g., "friendly-scanner").

   Matching is case-sensitive in both modes.

1.3. Dependencies

1.3.1. OpenSIPS Modules

   The following modules must be loaded before this module:
     * None.

1.3.2. External Libraries or Applications

   The following libraries or applications must be installed
   before running OpenSIPS with this module loaded:
     * None.

1.4. Exported Parameters

1.4.1. blacklist_file (string)

   Path to the blacklist file. One entry per line. Lines starting
   with # are treated as comments. Blank lines are ignored. This
   parameter is required.

   Default value is "None" (must be set).

   Example 1.1. Set blacklist_file parameter
...
modparam("rust_dynamic_blacklist", "blacklist_file", "/etc/opensips/blacklist.txt")
...

   Example 1.3. Blacklist file format
# /etc/opensips/blacklist.txt
# IP addresses
192.168.1.100
10.0.0.
# User-Agent strings
friendly-scanner
SIPVicious
# Domains
sip.spam.example.com

1.4.2. match_mode (string)

   The matching algorithm to use:

     * "exact" - value must match a blacklist entry exactly
       (case-sensitive). Uses a HashSet for O(1) lookups.
     * "prefix" - value must start with a blacklist entry
       (case-sensitive). Uses linear prefix matching.

   Default value is "prefix".

   Example 1.2. Set match_mode parameter
...
modparam("rust_dynamic_blacklist", "match_mode", "exact")
...

1.5. Exported Functions

1.5.1. rust_check_blacklist(value)

   Check whether the given value matches any entry in the
   blacklist. The matching behavior depends on the match_mode
   parameter.

   Parameters:
     * value (string) - The value to check against the blacklist.
       Typically a pseudo-variable such as $si (source IP), $ua
       (User-Agent), or $rd (domain). This parameter is mandatory.

   Return values:
     * 1 - value is NOT in the blacklist (allowed)
     * -1 - value IS in the blacklist (blocked), or error

   Note: The return value convention is "positive = allowed" so
   that typical usage reads naturally as an if-condition.

   This function can be used from REQUEST_ROUTE, FAILURE_ROUTE,
   and ONREPLY_ROUTE.

   Example 1.4. rust_check_blacklist usage
...
route {
    if (!rust_check_blacklist("$si")) {
        xlog("L_WARN", "blocked source IP $si\n");
        sl_send_reply(403, "Forbidden");
        exit;
    }
}
...

1.6. Exported Statistics

1.6.1. checked

   Total number of blacklist lookups performed.

1.6.2. blocked

   Number of lookups that matched the blacklist (traffic blocked).

1.6.3. allowed

   Number of lookups that did not match the blacklist (traffic
   allowed).

1.6.4. entries

   Number of entries loaded from the blacklist file at startup.

   Example 1.5. Complete opensips.cfg example -- IP blacklist
...
loadmodule "rust_dynamic_blacklist.so"

modparam("rust_dynamic_blacklist", "blacklist_file", "/etc/opensips/ip_blacklist.txt")
modparam("rust_dynamic_blacklist", "match_mode", "prefix")

route {
    # Block blacklisted source IPs (prefix mode catches subnets)
    if (!rust_check_blacklist("$si")) {
        xlog("L_WARN", "BLOCKED: source IP $si matched blacklist\n");
        sl_send_reply(403, "Forbidden");
        exit;
    }
}
...

   Example 1.6. Complete opensips.cfg example -- User-Agent blacklist
...
loadmodule "rust_dynamic_blacklist.so"

modparam("rust_dynamic_blacklist", "blacklist_file", "/etc/opensips/ua_blacklist.txt")
modparam("rust_dynamic_blacklist", "match_mode", "prefix")

route {
    # Block known scanner User-Agent strings
    if (is_present_hf("User-Agent")) {
        if (!rust_check_blacklist("$ua")) {
            xlog("L_WARN", "BLOCKED: User-Agent $ua matched blacklist\n");
            sl_send_reply(403, "Forbidden");
            exit;
        }
    }
}
...
